Not everyone makes a good stay home parent. <br>
<br>
I stayed home with Samantha for 6 months after she was born--I was lucky, I got 6 months 100% paid leave. I could not have gone back to work--there was no way I could've left her at that age. I went back 10 hours a week, at night, when she was 6 months old, and have gradually increased my hours over the past 3 years until now, and I am working full time again. She is perfectly able to handle this now, and she is in preschool twice a week anyway. I, for one, was not very happy being solely stay-home. I missed the power, and control I had at work, and liked being in that &quot;mode&quot; again.<br>
I was happy being back at work, and I think being a happy parent is way better than being a miserable parent that's home 24/7.<br>
<br>
And obviously, being atheist, I have no religious views on the matter, except for thinking it's sad when women who truly *don't* want to be stay-home-moms DO stay home, simply because they think it's what they should do, and become miserable. I think that's a shame, for both mom and the rest of the family.<br>
Emmy <p><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;I'm a goddamned marvel of modern science!!&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gaia25>Gaia25</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 22<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/2/03 3:20 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Calling All Stay @ Home Moms</span><hr size=1> I totally agree with Emmy on the &quot;happy parent = better parent, and not everyone is happy staying at home&quot; point.<br>
